                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/10/hallelujah-train-comes-hayti" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/10/hallelujah-train-comes-hayti&amp;text=Hallelujah Train comes to Hayti" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Hallelujah%20Train%20comes%20to%20Hayti%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2009%2F10%2Fhallelujah-train-comes-hayti" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>Brian Blade and his father, Pastor Brady Blade, Sr., have telling voices. The former speaks calmly and with a smooth tone, interjecting the occasional jazz musician&rsquo;s &ldquo;man.&rdquo; The elder Blade&rsquo;s voice reveals years in the ministry, and even treating me to a &ldquo;Praise God!&rdquo; in our conversation.</p>
<p>But what connects them, beyond their obvious kinship, is music.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>&ldquo;He grew up listening to my music and my singing, and it made a great impression on him,&rdquo; the pastor said of the younger Blade.</p>
<p>On Saturday and Sunday, over two performances and one service, father and son will come together in Durham in a project commissioned by Duke Performances called <em>The Hallelujah Train</em>.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Conceived by Brian, the project celebrates his father&rsquo;s nearly 50-year history as the pastor of the Zion Baptist Church in Shreveport, La. Brian took the drummer&rsquo;s chair at the congregation when he was 13 (his older brother, Brady Blade, Jr.&mdash;also coming for the performance&mdash;had just left for college). He grew up surrounded by his father&rsquo;s music and said some iteration of the project has always been on his mind.</p>
<p>But the younger Blade, now 39, went off and built a career as one of the most successful drummers in music, working with Bill Frisell, Joni Mitchell, producer Daniel Lanois (also playing this weekend) and his own Fellowship Band. It&rsquo;s now coming back to the beginning. Blade said the project is all about his father, his ministry and his &ldquo;God-given talent&rdquo; to preach through song.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My dad&mdash;when he gets going, it&rsquo;s great and just inspiring to me to see someone with conviction, with the goods to back it up, come and deliver something from deep inside,&rdquo; Brian said.</p>
<p><em>The Hallelujah Train</em> is more than a son admiring his father, though. Named after a show the pastor hosted in the late &rsquo;70s and early &rsquo;80s in which choirs and bands from Ark-La-Tex would play, the two performances will be recorded for a live album.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>&ldquo;It brings back not what&rsquo;s been lost in memory, but what&rsquo;s been lost in terms of documents. It&rsquo;s a bit of a revival of sorts,&rdquo; Brian said. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to have the regret that I didn&rsquo;t do my part to try and document what I&rsquo;ve been blessed with.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Director of Duke Performances Aaron Greenwald added that it&rsquo;s very unusual for universities or promoters to commission live albums.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Generally, what folks at universities or big presenting institutions want to commission are marquee pieces,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;But I felt like this was a unique opportunity that fit well with...the kind of music and culture we ought to be celebrating.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Indeed, <em>The Hallelujah Train</em> is the ultimate manifestation of Duke Performances&rsquo; current season, which is exploring modernism through the African diaspora.&nbsp;</p>
                            

<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="fdab49f43c">
    <h3>Get The Dirt</h3>
    <p>Subscribe to our weekly email about what&#039;s trending at Duke</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=fdab49f43c" method="post">
                <div class="input-group">
                    <input type="email" name="EMAIL" class="form-control form-control-sm" placeholder="Your email address" />
